Kernel Convolution

Notes and things to add

Why would we want to use this model?

  • can create valid positive definite covariance structures with desired properties
  • non-stationary
  • directional covariances for stream flow
  • fast to compute
  • Models similar to kernel convolution
  • dimension reduction techniques like fixed rank kriging and predictive process

Higdon model

The generic mixed model representation for spatially correlated random variables can be written as \[ \mathbf{y}(\mathbf{s}) = \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s}) \boldsymbol{\beta} + \boldsymbol{\eta}(\mathbf{s}) + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}, \] where \(\mathbf{y}(\mathbf{s})\) represents data observed at a vector of spatial locations \(\mathbf{s} \in \mathbf{\mathcal{S}}\).

The matrix \(\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s})\) represents spatially varying covariates with associated regression coefficients \(\boldsymbol{\beta}\). Taking a kernel convolution approach to the spatially correlated random effect \(\boldsymbol{\eta}(\mathbf{s})\) yields the relationship \[ \eta(\mathbf{s}_i) = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}) \,dW(\mathbf{u}), \mbox{ for } \mathbf{s}_i \in \mathbf{\mathcal{S}}. \] where \(dW(\mathbf{u})\) is the measure induced by the Wiener process \(W\). Given square integrability of the kernel function \(k(\cdot)\), the above representation induces the covariance function \[ \mbox{Cov}(\eta(\mathbf{s}_i), \eta(\mathbf{s}_j)) = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_i) k(\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{s}_i) \,dW(\mathbf{u}) \,dW(\mathbf{v}). \\ \] Then, using the hueristic understanding of the Wiener integral (details are far beyond any practical concern) that \(\int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \,dW(\mathbf{u}) \,dW(\mathbf{v}) = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \,d\mathbf{u}\), we have \[ \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_i) k(\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{s}_i) \,dW(\mathbf{u}) \,dW(\mathbf{v}) = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_i) k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_j) \,d\mathbf{u}, \mbox{ for } \mathbf{u} \in \mathbf{\mathcal{S}}. \] The kernel convolution approach is capable of creating models of many common covariance functions, including the Mátern class covariance functions that include the exponential, Gaussian, and spherical covariance functions. For example, consider the Gaussian covariance matrix whose \(ij^{th}\) element is \(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{ij}(\phi) = \exp{\{ - \frac{\phi d_{ij}^2} {2} \}}\) where \(d_{ij}\) is the Euclidean distance between locations \(\mathbf{s}_i\) and \(\mathbf{s}_j\). The kernel that gives rise to the Gaussian covariance \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) is the Gaussian kernel \(k(\mathbf{u}) = \frac{1} {\sqrt{2 \pi}} \exp{\{ - \frac{1} {2} \mathbf{u}' \mathbf{u} \} }\). Then, we can show the equivalence \[ \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_i) k(\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_j) \,d\mathbf{u} = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \frac{1} {\sqrt{2 \pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1} {2} (\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_i)' (\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_i) \right\} } \frac{1} {\sqrt{2 \pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1} {2} (\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_j)' (\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{s}_j) \right\} } \,d\mathbf{u} \\ = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \frac{1} {2 \pi} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1}{2} \left(2 \left(\mathbf{u}' \mathbf{u} - 2 \mathbf{u}'\frac{(\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j)}{2} \right) + (\mathbf{s}_i' \mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j' \mathbf{s}_j) \right) \right\} } \,d\mathbf{u} \\ = \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \frac{1} {2 \pi} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1}{2} \left(2 \left(\mathbf{u}' \mathbf{u} - 2 \mathbf{u}' \frac{\left(\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j \right)}{2} + \frac{1} {4} (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j)' (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j) - \frac{1} {4} (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j)' (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j) \right) + (\mathbf{s}_i' \mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j'\mathbf{s}_j) \right) \right\} } \,d\mathbf{u} \\ = \frac{1} {2 \sqrt{\pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1}{2}\left( - \frac{1}{2} (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j)' (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j) + (\mathbf{s}_i' \mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j' \mathbf{s}_j) \right) \right\} } \int_{\mathbf{\mathcal{S}}} \frac{1} {\sqrt{\pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \left( \mathbf{u} - (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j) \right)' \left( \mathbf{u} - (\mathbf{s}_i + \mathbf{s}_j) \right) \right\} } \\ = \frac{1} {2 \sqrt{\pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1}{4} \left( \mathbf{s}_i' \mathbf{s}_i - 2 \mathbf{s}_i' \mathbf{s}_j + \mathbf{s}_j' \mathbf{s}_j \right) \right\} } \\ = \frac{1} {2 \sqrt{\pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1}{4} (\mathbf{s}_i - \mathbf{s}_j)' (\mathbf{s}_i - \mathbf{s}_j) \right\} } \\ = \frac{1} {2 \sqrt{2\pi}} \exp{ \left\{ - \frac{1}{4} d_{ij}^2 \right\} }, \] thus the Gaussian kernel convolution results in a Gaussian covariance function with variance parameter of \(\frac{1}{2}\).

The above model can be re-written as \[ \mathbf{y}(\mathbf{s}) = \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s}) \boldsymbol{\beta} + \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}, \] where the spatially correlated random effect \(\boldsymbol{\eta}(\mathbf{s})\) is replaced by the matrix \(\mathbf{K}\) where the \(ij^{th}\) elements of \(\mathbf{K}\) are the normal density \(\boldsymbol{\Phi}(\mathbf{u}_i - \mathbf{s}_j)\) evaluated at the distance between knot location \(\mathbf{u}_i\) and observation location \(\mathbf{s}_j\) for a set of knots \(\mathbf{u} \in \mathbf{\mathcal{U}}\). The matrix \(\mathbf{K}\) is multiplied by a mean zero white noise Gaussian random effect \(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\), forming a discrete approximation to the kernel convolution process.

Higdon model fit

# a fake dataset to make the bumps
n <- 30
m <- 7
s_full <- seq(1, 10, length = 1000)
s <- seq(1, 10, length = n)
# create the data
e1 <- rnorm(n, sd=0.1)
e2 <- cos(s / 10 * 2 * pi * 4) * 0.2
e2_full <- cos(s_full / 10 * 2 * pi * 4) * 0.2
y <- sin(s / 10 * 2 * pi) + e1 + e2
z_full <- sin(s_full / 10 * 2 * pi) + e2_full
# plot(y ~ s, type = 'l')
# lines(z_full ~ s_full, col = 'green')
# location of support points
w <- seq(1 - 2, 10+2, length = m)
# width of kernel
sdkern <- 2
# create the matrix K
K <- matrix(NA, ncol=m, nrow=n)
for(i in 1:m){
  K[, i] <- dnorm(s, mean = w[i], sd = sdkern)
}
# create a dataframe to hold the data
df1 <- data.frame(y=y, K=K, sub=1)
df1$sub <- as.factor(df1$sub)
# now fit a mixed model using lme
# a1 <- lme(fixed=y ~ 1, random=pdIdent(~ K - 1), data=df1, na.action=na.omit)
a1 <- lme(fixed=y ~ 1, random=list(sub = pdIdent(~ K - 1)), data=df1, na.action=na.omit)
# lmer(y ~ 1 + (K - 1  ), data=df1)
# obtain and plot the fitted values
a1p <- as.vector(predict(a1, df1))
# lines(s, a1p, lty = 1, col = 'red')

# now a multiscale version
m1 <- c(7, 14, 28)  # number of knot upport points at each scale
w <- list(NULL)  # list to hold the knot locations
# make support locations w
for(i in 1:3){
  w[[i]] <- seq(1-2, 10+2, length = m1[i])
}
sdkern <- c(2, 1, 0.5) # kernel width by scale
# generate K matrices for each scale
K1 <- matrix(NA, ncol=m1[1], nrow=n)
for(i in 1:m1[1]){
  K1[, i] <- dnorm(s, mean=w[[1]][i], sd=sdkern[1])
}
K2 <- matrix(NA, ncol=m1[2], nrow=n)
for(i in 1:m1[2]){
  K2[, i] <- dnorm(s, mean=w[[2]][i], sd=sdkern[2])
}
K3 <- matrix(NA, ncol=m1[3], nrow=n)
for(i in 1:m1[3]){
  K3[, i] <- dnorm(s, mean=w[[3]][i], sd=sdkern[3])
}
# create dataframe df2
df2 <- data.frame(y=y, K1=K1, K2=K2, K3=K3, sub=1)
# fit mixed effects model
a2 <- lme(fixed=y ~ 1, random=list(sub = pdIdent(~ K1 - 1), sub = pdIdent(~ K2 - 1), sub = pdIdent(~ K3 - 1)), data=df2, na.action=na.omit)
# get predictions
a2p <- as.vector(predict(a2, df2))
# plots
plot(s, y, type = 'n', main = "Higdon Example")
points(s, y)
lines(s, a1p, col = 'red')
lines(s, a2p, col = 'blue')
lines(s_full, z_full, col = 'darkgreen')
legend(x="topright", legend=c("truth", "one scale", "multiscale"), col=c("red", "blue", "darkgreen"), lty=1)
rug(s)

Simulate some data from a traditional geostatistical model

We simulate data from the traditional geostatistical model

\[ \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} + \boldsymbol{\eta} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \]

where the spatially correlated random error is given by \(\boldsymbol{\eta} \sim \mbox{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\eta} \mathbf{R}(\boldsymbol{\theta}))\) for a Mátern class correlation function \(\mathbf{R}(\boldsymbol{\theta})\) and the independent error is \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mbox{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\epsilon} \mathbf{I})\). For our simulation we use an Exponential correlation where the \(ij^{th}\) element of the covariance matrix \(\mathbf{R}_{ij}(\mathbf{\theta}) = \exp{ \{ - \phi * d_{ij}\} }\) where \(d_{ij}\) is the Euclidean distance between locations \(i\) and \(j\).

For this example we allow for \(\mathbf{\beta}\) to have an intercept \(\beta_0\), regression parameter \(\beta_1\) uncorrelated with the spatial random effect, and a regression parameter \(\beta_2\) highly correlated with the spatial random effect.

Now let’s examine a hierarchical Bayesian model for kernel convolution.

Data model

\[ \mathbf{y}(\mathbf{s}) = \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s}) \boldsymbol{\beta} + \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}, \] where \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon} \sim \mathbf{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\epsilon} \mathbf{I})\)

Complete pooling model

Priors

\[ \boldsymbol{\beta} \sim \mathbf{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\beta} \mathbf{I}) \\ \boldsymbol{\alpha} \sim \mathbf{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\alpha} \mathbf{I}) \\ \sigma^2_\epsilon \sim \mathbf{IG}(\alpha_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}}, \beta_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}}) \\ \sigma^2_\beta \sim \mathbf{IG}(\alpha_{\sigma^2_{\beta}}, \beta_{\sigma^2_{\beta}}) \\ \sigma^2_\alpha \sim \mathbf{IG}(\alpha_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}}, \beta_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}}) \\ \]

Appendix

Full conditionals for the complete pooling Bayesian Hierarchical Kernel convolution model

Full conditional for \(\boldsymbol{\beta}\)

\[ [\boldsymbol{\beta} | \cdot] \propto [\mathbf{y} | \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_\epsilon] [\boldsymbol{\beta} | \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}},\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\beta}] \\ \propto \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})\} } \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}})' {\Sigma}_{\beta}^{ - 1} (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}}) \} } \\ \propto \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} [ \boldsymbol{\beta}' (\mathbf{X}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} \mathbf{X} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\beta}^{ - 1}) \boldsymbol{\beta} - 2 \boldsymbol{\beta}' (\mathbf{X}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha}) ] \} } \\ \] which is N\((\mathbf{A}^{ - 1} \mathbf{b}, \mathbf{A}^{ - 1})\) where \[ \mathbf{A} = \mathbf{X}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} \mathbf{X} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\beta}^{ - 1} = \frac{\mathbf{X}'\mathbf{X}} {\sigma^2_\epsilon} - \frac{1} {\sigma^2_\beta} \mathbf {I} \\ \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{X}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha}) = \frac{\mathbf{X}' (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})} {\sigma^2_\epsilon} \\ \]

Full conditional for \(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\)

\[ [\boldsymbol{\alpha} | \cdot] \propto [\mathbf{y} | \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_\epsilon] [\boldsymbol{\alpha} | \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}},\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\alpha}] \\ \propto \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})\} } \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}})' {\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{ - 1} (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}}) \} } \\ \propto \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} [ \boldsymbol{\alpha}' (\mathbf{K}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} \mathbf{K} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{ - 1}) \boldsymbol{\alpha} - 2 \boldsymbol{\alpha}' (\mathbf{K}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta}) ] \} } \\ \] which is N\((\mathbf{A}^{ - 1} \mathbf{b}, \mathbf{A}^{ - 1})\) where \[ \mathbf{A} = \mathbf{K}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} \mathbf{K} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{ - 1} = \frac{\mathbf{K}'\mathbf{K}} {\sigma^2_\epsilon} - \frac{1} {\sigma^2_\alpha} \mathbf {I} \\ \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{K}' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta}) = \frac{\mathbf{K}' (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta})} {\sigma^2_\epsilon} \\ \]

Full conditional for \(\sigma^2_{\epsilon}\)

\[ [\sigma^2_{\epsilon} | \cdot] \propto [\mathbf{y} | \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_\epsilon] [\sigma^2_{\epsilon}] \\ \propto |\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}|^{ - \frac{1}{2}} \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\epsilon}^{ - 1} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha}) \} } {\sigma^2_{\epsilon}}^{ - \alpha_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}} - 1} \exp{\{ - \frac{\beta_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}}}{\sigma^2_\epsilon} \}} \\ \] \[\propto (\sigma^2_{\epsilon})^{ - \alpha_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}} - \frac{p}{2} - 1} \exp{ \{ -\frac{1}{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}}[ \beta_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}} + \frac{1} {2} (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})' (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha}) ] \} } \\ \] which is IG\((\alpha_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}} + \frac{n} {2}, \beta_{\sigma^2_{\epsilon}} + \frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha})' (\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X} \boldsymbol{\beta} - \mathbf{K} \boldsymbol{\alpha}) )\)

Full conditional for \(\sigma^2_{\beta}\)

\[ [\sigma^2_{\beta} | \cdot] \propto [\boldsymbol{\beta} | \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}},\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\beta}] [\sigma^2_{\beta}] \\ \propto |\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\beta}|^{ - \frac{1}{2}} \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}})' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\beta}^{ - 1} (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}}) \} } {\sigma^2_{\beta}}^{ - \alpha_{\sigma^2_{\beta}} - 1} \exp{\{ - \frac{\beta_{\sigma^2_{\beta}}}{\sigma^2_\beta} \}} \\ \] \[\propto (\sigma^2_{\beta})^{ - \alpha_{\sigma^2_{\beta}} - \frac{p}{2} - 1} \exp{ \{ -\frac{1}{\sigma^2_{\beta}}[ \beta_{\sigma^2_{\beta}} + \frac{1} {2} (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}})' (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}}) ] \} } \\ \] which is IG\((\alpha_{\sigma^2_{\beta}} + \frac{p} {2}, \beta_{\sigma^2_{\beta}} + \frac{1}{2} (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}})' (\boldsymbol{\beta} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\beta}}) )\)

Full conditional for \(\sigma^2_{\alpha}\)

\[ [\sigma^2_{\alpha} | \cdot] \propto [\boldsymbol{\alpha} | \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}},\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\alpha}] [\sigma^2_{\alpha}] \\ \propto |\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\alpha}|^{ - \frac{1}{2}} \exp{ \{ - \frac{1} {2} (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}})' \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{ - 1} (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}}) \} } {\sigma^2_{\alpha}}^{ - \alpha_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}} - 1} \exp{\{ - \frac{\beta_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}}}{\sigma^2_\alpha} \}} \\ \] \[\propto (\sigma^2_{\alpha})^{ - \alpha_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}} - \frac{p}{2} - 1} \exp{ \{ -\frac{1}{\sigma^2_{\alpha}}[ \beta_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}} + \frac{1} {2} (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}})' (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}}) ] \} } \\ \] which is IG\((\alpha_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}} + \frac{p} {2}, \beta_{\sigma^2_{\alpha}} + \frac{1}{2} (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}})' (\boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\mu_{\alpha}}) )\)
